@page "/guide"

<PageTitle>Guide</PageTitle>

<div class="guide-container">
<div class="container py-4">

    <h1 class="mb-4">Breeder Guide</h1>

    <p>
        Here I will explain how to use this breeder, along with some examples.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-4">What is this?</h2>

    <p>
        This is a <strong>Lossless Deterministic Pokémon Breeder</strong>. Let's start by explaining these terms:
    </p>

    <h3>Lossless</h3>

    <p>
        The result will never "lose" a characteristic that you have defined as important.
        Importance is determined through what we call <strong>Configurations</strong>,
        which will be explained later.
    </p>

    <h3>Deterministic</h3>

    <p>
        The result is always guaranteed. This application does not rely on chance-based
        breeding outcomes or random results.
    </p>

    <h3>Combination</h3>

    <p>
        A combination is the result of breeding two Pokémon together. This term is used
        throughout the application for clarity.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>General</h2>

        <p>
            Any field marked with a red asterisk (<span style="color:red">*</span>) is required and must be completed before
            you can continue or save.
        </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>Pokémon</h2>

    <p>
        The <strong>Pokémon</strong> tab is used to enter Pokémon and their information.
        This includes:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>Nature</li>
        <li>Gender</li>
        <li>IVs</li>
        <li>Alpha status</li>
        <li>Hidden Ability</li>
        <li>Particles</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        You can also assign nicknames to your Pokémon. These are used to make it easier
        to identify specific Pokémon within the application.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>Configurations</h2>

    <p>
        This is where you define the requirements a Pokémon must meet, as well as which characteristics are important and must be preserved during breeding.
    </p>

    <p>You can also:</p>

    <ul>
        <li>Define an Egg Group.</li>
        <li>Filter results to show only Alpha or non-Alpha Pokémon.</li>
        <li>Select one or more Natures.</li>
        <li>Define a valid range for each IV.</li>
        <li>Ignore specific IVs if they are not important for your breeding goal.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr />

    <h2>Daycare</h2>

    <p>
        This is where you generate breeding combinations.
    </p>

    <p>
        First, select an existing configuration. Once selected, you can combine all
        Pokémon that meet that configuration's requirements.
    </p>

    <p>
        Most information is calculated automatically, including:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>Whether the resulting Pokémon is Alpha.</li>
        <li>Whether it has a Hidden Ability.</li>
        <li>Particle inheritance.</li>
        <li>The resulting species.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        IVs and Nature that are guaranteed to be inherited through breeding items are
        automatically highlighted in red. The rest must be selected manually.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>Combination Results</h2>

    <p>
        Within the results screen you can:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>View the parents of each combination.</li>
        <li>Filter combinations by parent.</li>
        <li>
            Enter the information obtained after performing the actual breeding:
            <ul>
                <li>Final IVs (unless they are guaranteed by inheritance).</li>
                <li>Nature (unless it is guaranteed by inheritance).</li>
                <li>Gender.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>
            Save the resulting Pokémon and automatically add it to your Pokémon collection.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <hr />

    <h2>Examples</h2>

    <div>
        <strong>Important:</strong> The application assumes that breeding items
        (Braces and Everstone) are being used.
    </div>

    <h2 class="mt-4">Configuration 1</h2>

    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="assets/image1.png"
                alt="Configuration 1"
                class="img-fluid rounded border" />
    </div>

    <p>
        This is the most basic configuration possible. It can be summarized as:
    </p>

    <blockquote class="blockquote">
        <p>"Combine any Pokémon with compatible 31 IVs."</p>
    </blockquote>

    <p>
        In the examples below, <strong>X</strong> means any value lower than 31.
        The exact value is irrelevant.
    </p>

    <h3>Example 1</h3>

    <h5>Pokémon A</h5>

    <p>
        31 HP - X Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
    </p>

    <h5>Pokémon B</h5>

    <p>
        31 HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - X Speed
    </p>

    <p>
        The system determines that these two Pokémon can be combined without losing
        any required 31 IVs. The result will be:
    </p>

    <h5>Combination</h5>

    <p class="fw-bold">
        31 HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
    </p>

    <h3 class="mt-4">Example 2</h3>

    <h5>Pokémon A</h5>

    <p>
        31 HP - X Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
    </p>

    <h5>Pokémon B</h5>

    <p>
        X HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - X Speed
    </p>

    <p>
        The system determines that these two Pokémon cannot be combined because there
        is a risk of losing either the 31 HP IV or the 31 Speed IV (depending on which
        Brace is used). Therefore, no valid result will be generated.
    </p>

    <p>
        Now let's change the configuration to:
    </p>

    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="assets/image2.png"
                alt="Configuration 2"
                class="img-fluid rounded border" />
    </div>

    <h3>Example 3</h3>

    <h5>Pokémon A</h5>

    <p>
        31 HP - X Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
    </p>

    <h5>Pokémon B</h5>

    <p>
        26 HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - X Speed
    </p>

    <p>
        The system determines that these two Pokémon can be combined without losing
        the HP IV requirement because the resulting HP IV is guaranteed to be at least
        25, which is the minimum value defined in the configuration.
    </p>

    <p>
        The other two important IVs can be inherited through the use of Braces.
    </p>

    <h5>Combination</h5>

    <p class="fw-bold">
        26-31 HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
    </p>

    <p>
        We can also create configurations where all defensive IVs must be between
        25 and 31, or even configurations where every IV must be between 25 and 31
        if that matches our breeding goals.
    </p>

    <p>
        This application also supports more specialized configurations.
    </p>

    <div class="text-center mb-4">
        <img src="assets/image3.png"
                alt="Configuration 3"
                class="img-fluid rounded border" />
    </div>

    <p>
        In this configuration, we are looking for physical attackers in the Field
        Egg Group. Defense-related IVs do not need to be perfect (31), and values
        of 25 or higher are acceptable.
    </p>

    <h3>Example 4</h3>

    <h5>Pokémon A</h5>

    <p>
        X HP - X Attack - 25 Defense - 5 Sp. Attack - 27 Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
    </p>

    <h5>Pokémon B</h5>

    <p>
        X HP - 31 Attack - 28 Defense - 31 Sp. Attack - 30 Sp. Defense - X Speed
    </p>

    <h5>Combination</h5>

    <p class="fw-bold">
        X HP - 31 Attack - 25-28 Defense - 5-31 Sp. Attack - 27-30 Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
    </p>

    <p>
        In this case, because the Sp. Attack IV has been marked as ignored, the
        combination is allowed to lose the 31 IV in that stat.
    </p>

    <p>
        Remember: the breeder will never lose a characteristic that you have marked
        as important. Since Sp. Attack was configured to be ignored, it is not
        considered when validating breeding combinations.
    </p>

        <h3 class="mt-4">Example 5</h3>

        <h5>Pokémon A</h5>

        <p>
            X HP - X Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
            <br />
            Nature: Adamant
        </p>

        <h5>Pokémon B</h5>

        <p>
            X HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - X Speed
        </p>

        <p>
            The system determines that these two Pokémon cannot be combined.
            In this configuration, both the Adamant Nature and the 31 Speed IV are
            marked as important characteristics.
        </p>

        <p>
            Because only one breeding item can be used to guarantee inheritance, there is no way to
            guarantee both the Adamant Nature and the 31 Speed IV. Therefore, no valid result will be generated.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mt-4">Example 6</h3>

        <h5>Pokémon A</h5>

        <p>
            X HP - X Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
            <br />
            Nature: Adamant
        </p>

        <h5>Pokémon B</h5>

        <p>
            X HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
        </p>

        <h5>Combination</h5>

        <p class="fw-bold">
            X HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
            <br />
            Nature: Adamant
        </p>

        <p>
            In this case, both parents already have a 31 Speed IV. Because the Speed IV
            requirement is already satisfied by both Pokémon, the breeding items can be
            used to guarantee inheritance of the 31 Attack IV and the Adamant Nature.
        </p>

        <p>
            As a result, the combination preserves all important characteristics and is
            considered valid.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mt-4">Example 7</h3>

        <h5>Pokémon A</h5>

        <p>
            X HP - X Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
            <br />
            Nature: Adamant
        </p>

        <h5>Pokémon B</h5>

        <p>
            X HP - 31 Attack - X Defense - X Sp. Attack - X Sp. Defense - 31 Speed
            <br />
            Nature: Jolly
        </p>

        <p>
            The system determines that these two Pokémon cannot be combined.
        </p>

        <p>
            In this configuration, both Adamant and Jolly have been selected as valid
            Natures and are therefore considered important characteristics.
        </p>

        <p>
            Breeding these two Pokémon would inevitably result in the loss of one of the required Natures. Therefore, no valid result will
            be generated.
        </p>

</div>
</div>

